# .aidocs/coding-standards.aidocs - Global Coding Standards

## Baseline Rules
- Work only inside Root (the directory containing `AIDOCS.md`) unless explicitly instructed otherwise.
- Prefer existing patterns and reuse over new abstractions.
- KISS: keep it stupidly simple (so simple that even stupid can understand).
- Keep changes minimal, focused, and reversible.
- Avoid adding comments unless the logic is non-obvious.

## Data-Driven Design
- Do not hardcode business rules or scoped fields in general/shared code.
- Prefer using the generalized domain entities/config (e.g., tenant/org/workspace + role/level definitions) as data.
- If you find yourself adding special-case fields/branches for one tenant/customer, stop and propose a generalized approach.

## Reuse Over Reinvent
- Prefer reusing existing project interfaces (CLI/server APIs/tools) over adding new parallel implementations.

## Reuse (General)
- Default to reuse: if the project already has a way to do something (module, service, CLI, API), use it.
- Only introduce a new path when the existing one cannot meet the requirements; explain why.

## Agent Defaults
- If a rule is ambiguous, ask for the smallest missing detail before proceeding.
- Prefer simple, local changes over large refactors unless explicitly requested.
- If you discover unexpected architecture, pause and re-scope before editing.

## Debugging And Errors
- When the user provides an error (stack trace, log, failing command), first explain WHY the error appeared in plain terms.
- If the cause is 100% clear, then fix the error.
- If the cause is not 100% clear, ask for the smallest missing detail before making risky changes.

## Documentation Expectations
- Project documentation should include an index file.
- Keep routing concise and actionable.
- When documentation and code disagree, report both options with rationale.

## Data (NF)
- Prefer database designs that follow normal forms (NF1..NF5) unless there is a clear, documented reason to denormalize.
